            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "No. This number is quite arbitrary. The amount of git clones we can make could be much larger than this and depends on factors other than the amount of physical threads on a CPU. For network heavy jobs, I'm fairly confident 1 CPU can manage lots since it'll be sleeping most of the time anyway waiting for data packets. It'll be things like network bandwidth, IO bandwidth/latency that'll determine the real bottleneck.",
            "commit_id": "1152c678fe4f0b2011c940b09588078c30fe648d",
            "created_at": "2026-04-05T18:37:08Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -499,9 +499,17 @@ local function new_progress_report(action)\n   end)\n end\n \n-local n_threads = 2 * #(uv.cpu_info() or { {} })\n local copcall = package.loaded.jit and pcall or require('coxpcall').pcall\n \n+local function async_join_run_wait(funs)\n+  local n_threads = 2 * (uv.available_parallelism() or 1)",
